<h1>Solving the toilet shortage problem at parties</h1>

<div class="row">
    <div class="col-xs-12 col-sm-6 col-md-6 col-lg-6">

        <p>At every party there is generally a high demand for toilet facilities. The number of those at the party is large compared to the number of flatmates who live in the flat. The majority of people will be drinking alcohol, which is a diuretic that dehydrates the body and causes a higher rate of urination. This means that there will be a queue, with a wait that is not acceptable and results in the need to urinate outside. At student parties, it is most likely that all of the guests are fine with others doing this nearby. The problem comes when there may not be a discreet garden area or where there is visibility to other flats and the street. Neighbours or the public not at the party could be offended, and it could lead to an unintentional indecent exposure. For these situations, it would be ideal to have other options, such as a way to collect urine where it would normally be inappropriate to urinate.</p>
      
    </div>        
    <div class="col-xs-12 col-sm-6 col-md-6 col-lg-6">      
        <p>There are a number of factors that either cause the shortage or make it more difficult for parties and may make particular options more appropriate. This would include any of the following factors:</p>
        
            <ul>
                <li>The flat has only one toilet (or a high demand if more than one is available)</li>
                <li>There is a small garden area with limited discreet areas</li>
                <li>The flat is close to other neighbours</li>
                <li>The outside area is clearly visible from the street</li>
            </ul>
        <p>The options that could be available at parties are as follows:</p>
            <ul>
                <li>Option 1: Wait in a queue for the main toilet(s) at the flat.</li>
                <li>Option 2: Find an appropriate place in the garden outside (urine only).</li>
                <li>Option 3: Create your own urinal collection device using items such as a bucket, funnel, or storage container.</li>
            </ul>
