        <p>Option 1 is considered as the most acceptable; however, it is unlikely to be suitable unless the queue clears in a few minutes or less. Any longer than this would be uncomfortable to wait.</p>
        <p>A major reason for limiting the demand for option 1 is due to some people needing to use the toilet for the other end. If there is only one toilet then it is almost guaranteed to be used continuously throughout the whole party.  There will generally be no other alternative at the party and those that are waiting, face both the discomfort of holding the bowel movement. Then once they get to the toilet, there is the pressure to take a short time, even though a few minutes is likely to be required. It would be great if the people waiting in the queue could instead go somewhere else, as urinating in a toilet is not absolutely essential. Finding a suitable alternative for those at the party is a key consideration to reduce the awkward situations that may occur at parties, which are generally unavoidable.</p>
        <p>Option 2 is an alternative if a toilet is not available. This is generally suitable where there are outdoor garden areas that are not visible from neighbouring flats or the street; however, it is not ideal urinating directly onto a garden as urine has a high concentration of chemicals such as nitrogen, which can be toxic to plants without being diluted. A person that has been drinking will have a higher concentration of chemicals, which is even more reason to avoid urinating directly onto the bushes in your garden. The odour from the urine will be obvious after being deposited on the garden.</p>
        <p>Option 3 is not normally used; although, it could provide a suitable alternative if there is not a suitable garden area outside. This could allow another indoor room, such as a laundry to be used, or an outdoor area with some privacy.</p>
        <p>One factor that would make option 3 seem unattractive is the potential for an odour to be present with the urine. In a normal situation, the urine would be odour free from people who are well hydrated. The trouble is that people drinking at parties are likely to be dehydrated, which is one reason for urine having odour. In this situation, the urine could be diluted by adding water to the container used, including the addition of vinegar if required.</p>
        <p>Option 4 would allow the urine to be directly used usefully for the production of compost. It avoids the need to urinate directly onto bushes with a concentrated load of urine chemicals and is a useful way to make use of the nutrients that would otherwise be wasted.</p>
        <p>Options 3 and 4 are identified as the most suitable alternatives as opposed to option 2 that involves urinating directly on the garden.</p>
