        <p>For option 3, a urine collection device would solve the problem as follows:</p>
            <ul>
                <li>Provides another place to pass urine and reduces the demand on the available toilet(s).</li>
                <li>Avoids the need to urinate directly onto the garden and potentially kill plants with the concentrated level of chemicals present in your urine.</li>
                <li>If there is no garden outside, and neighbours are close, then a discreet location can be selected that would not normally be acceptable to urinate on (such as another room inside, or somewhere discrete outside).</li>
            </ul>
        <p>For option 4, a compost heap would provide the key benefits as follows:</p>
            <ul>
                <li>People are able to urinate directly onto a heap designed to make the most of the nutrients present in urine.</li>
                <li>This can be justified as environmentally friendly, for those outside the party who have concerns about outdoor urination.</li>
                <li>The compost can eventually be used later for the garden, once it decomposes.</li>
            </ul>
        <p>The toilet shortage means that the main toilet in the flat is generally not sufficient to provide for all of the people at a party. This generally means that a fall back option is to find somewhere discreet in the garden outside. Instead of accepting that a highly concentrated liquid will be sprayed on the garden at your flat, it would be great to look for other options that avoid killing off plants, or make better use of the nutrients contained within. At your next party, it is time to be creative to come up with a solution that better meets the needs of your guests.</p>
       
